Iraqi President Saddam Hussein seemed

determined to solve his financial problems and fulfill territorial ambitions by dethroning the government of neighboring Kuwait.
The invasion, unprecedented in modern Arab history, reflected the brutality Saddam has used to crush all opposition at home since coming to power in 1979.
Oh God Almighty, be witness that we have warned them," he said last month after prices tumbled below $14 per barrel.
Saddam said he fought the war to protect the Arabs from the fundamentalist revolution fomented by the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini in Persian, mainly Shiite Moslem Iran.
Despite claims that the war was an unprecedented victory, the long conflict stalled Iraq's development, dragging on for eight years.
